    {
      "id": "77187c76bc0e056fe7e38ff17c1eb92b50c39d68",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-07 05:09:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nAlso do you know of any backstory wrt these helpers? Are there any plans to introduce some sort of locking later one that we need to get prepared to as we have some split nlink operations that do check and set?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "776c69ad4bfce43b865e223cefa3f2b6ebb32921",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 242,
        "name": "Liu Xuezhao",
        "email": "xuezhao.liu@emc.com",
        "username": "XuezhaoLiu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-11-07 07:03:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)\n\nI will update this patch to change inc_nlink to set_nlink when increasing it from 0 to 1 to avoid the WARN_ON.\n\n\"Also do you know of any backstory wrt these helpers? \"\n\nSeems the protection of i_nlink is just for similiar idea as object-oriented, the maintainer does not want people change it directly but should through kernel provided drop/clear/set/inc_nlink().\n\n\"Are there any plans to introduce some sort of locking later one that we need to get prepared to as we have some split nlink operations that do check and set?\"\n\nI checked that all cases in lustre that check and set i_nlink are already in protection by lock, so I think it is not a problem.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "3788e98b1df8ded0697aa0645a64f695b4620682",
      "author": {
